247
00:08:40,954 --> 00:08:42,487
         You do whatever        
         you want to do.        

248
00:08:42,489 --> 00:08:43,555
    You're dangerous, woman.    

249
00:08:43,557 --> 00:08:44,856
                 [ Laughs ]     

250
00:08:46,359 --> 00:08:49,294
     Up next, a funky-fresh     
         seafood spot...        

251
00:08:49,296 --> 00:08:51,363
      I mean, that's legit.     
      That's really legit.      

252
00:08:51,365 --> 00:08:53,698
        ...where cuisine        
     and crazy creativity...    

253
00:08:53,700 --> 00:08:56,034
You have got a big imagination, 
     my friend.                 

254
00:08:56,036 --> 00:08:57,235
           ...collide.          

255
00:08:57,237 --> 00:08:58,236
That looks like a roadside      
in Flavortown right there.      

256
00:09:02,709 --> 00:09:05,109
                     ♪♪         

257
00:09:05,111 --> 00:09:07,045
  So, on the next stop of this  
  "Triple D" New Orleans tour,  

258
00:09:07,047 --> 00:09:09,380
           here we are          
     in the city of Harahan.    

259
00:09:09,382 --> 00:09:11,383
   Now, it's about 20 minutes   
   from downtown New Orleans,   

260
00:09:11,385 --> 00:09:14,319
    and about 10 minutes away   
   from the River Shack Tavern  

261
00:09:14,321 --> 00:09:15,753
          that we shot          
         just years ago.        

262
00:09:15,755 --> 00:09:17,455
       Now, when you drive      
         by this place,         

263
00:09:17,457 --> 00:09:20,524
   first thing you can say is,  
       "Oh, hey, a shrimp       
       and po' boy joint."      

264
00:09:20,526 --> 00:09:22,927
 Don't judge a book by its cover
      for sure on this one,     

265
00:09:22,929 --> 00:09:25,196
       because they've got      
    chapters of culinary good   

266
00:09:25,198 --> 00:09:26,665
        that you've just        
       got to read about.       

267
00:09:26,667 --> 00:09:30,535
   This is Seither's Seafood.   

268
00:09:30,537 --> 00:09:32,403
I got a Peepaw salad.           

269
00:09:32,405 --> 00:09:34,538
   It's where people that are   
    from New Orleans go eat.    

270
00:09:34,540 --> 00:09:36,407
           One boiled           
        seafood platter.        

271
00:09:36,409 --> 00:09:38,610
        All your favorite       
    New Orleans-style dishes    

272
00:09:38,612 --> 00:09:40,345
      done in Jason's way.      

273
00:09:40,347 --> 00:09:42,680
    -That's Jason Seither...    
         -Make it snow!         

274
00:09:42,682 --> 00:09:45,616
  ...who grew up in the bayou,  
  boiling crawfish with his dad 

275
00:09:45,618 --> 00:09:47,418
   and cooking in the kitchen   
          with his mom.         

276
00:09:47,420 --> 00:09:49,754
               I'm respecting   
     the old-school ingredients,

277
00:09:49,756 --> 00:09:52,424
      but I'm just incorporating
           my own style into it.

278
00:09:52,426 --> 00:09:54,692
      -Here's the volcano.      
-A volcano is actually something

279
00:09:54,694 --> 00:09:56,560
        that I get almost       
       every time we come.      

280
00:09:56,562 --> 00:09:57,962
          It's a lot of         
         familiar things        

281
00:09:57,964 --> 00:09:59,564
       presented in a way       
         you never saw.         

282
00:09:59,566 --> 00:10:04,970
  The volcano is basically like 
an upside-down Asian taco salad.

283
00:10:04,972 --> 00:10:08,172
 Oh, you hear about             
  those every day.              

284
00:10:08,174 --> 00:10:10,642
   First, we're going to make   
    the blackening seasoning.   

285
00:10:10,644 --> 00:10:12,110
      I've got some paprika     
          right here...         

286
00:10:12,112 --> 00:10:13,311
  Some pap-a-rika.              

287
00:10:13,313 --> 00:10:16,114
        ...black pepper,        
    sea salt, parsley flakes,   

288
00:10:16,116 --> 00:10:18,583
        granulated onion,       
       granulated garlic,       

289
00:10:18,585 --> 00:10:20,118
            and then,           
     the Italian seasoning.     

290
00:10:20,120 --> 00:10:22,387
   Okay. So, now,               
we have the fresh Ahi.          

291
00:10:22,389 --> 00:10:24,122
             Right.             
         This is local.         

292
00:10:24,124 --> 00:10:26,257
So, if you can't get it fresh,  
you just won't be serving it?   

293
00:10:26,259 --> 00:10:28,393
     -That's exactly right.     
       -The best attitude.      

294
00:10:28,395 --> 00:10:29,927
We'll sear this off.            
     Next step?                 

295
00:10:29,929 --> 00:10:32,063
                Spicy mayo --   
       I call it "dragon sauce,"

296
00:10:32,065 --> 00:10:33,498
                just to have    
                a cool name.    

297
00:10:33,500 --> 00:10:35,800
       -All it is is mayo.      
         -And sriracha.         

298
00:10:35,802 --> 00:10:37,802
      I like to add a little bit
               of water to it   

299
00:10:37,804 --> 00:10:39,871
           because when I put it
         in the squeeze bottles,

300
00:10:39,873 --> 00:10:41,139
                I can, like,    
                draw with it.   

301
00:10:41,141 --> 00:10:42,607
I don't speak Cajun.            

302
00:10:42,609 --> 00:10:44,008
 That's how you say             
"draw with it" in Cajun?        

303
00:10:44,010 --> 00:10:45,209
         -Draw with it!         
             -Next?             

304
00:10:45,211 --> 00:10:46,811
        -The crab salad.        
             -Okay.             

305
00:10:46,813 --> 00:10:49,881
   I'm taking this shredded kani
   that they use in sushi rolls.

306
00:10:49,883 --> 00:10:51,415
So, this is pollock.            

307
00:10:51,417 --> 00:10:54,686
      Take some of this sauce --
The Cajun measuring system.     

308
00:10:54,688 --> 00:10:56,287
                   Right?       

309
00:10:56,289 --> 00:10:57,756
   All right, so, I'm gonna show
   you how to make this volcano.

310
00:10:57,758 --> 00:10:59,423
  I am on the edge              
     of my seat.                

311
00:10:59,425 --> 00:11:00,958
          -Here we go.          
           -Gorgeous!           

312
00:11:00,960 --> 00:11:02,761
               Fillet the tuna  
                around here,    

313
00:11:02,763 --> 00:11:05,429
              avocados, lettuce 
            right in the middle.

314
00:11:05,431 --> 00:11:06,765
               Put the shrimp   
                  on there,     

315
00:11:06,767 --> 00:11:11,369
    the spicy mayo that we made,
            eel sauce, sriracha.

316
00:11:11,371 --> 00:11:12,437
     I'm dizzy.                 

317
00:11:12,439 --> 00:11:15,173
            Take the taco shell,
            turn it upside down.

318
00:11:15,175 --> 00:11:17,575
               Put some of the  
         snow crab salad on top,

319
00:11:17,577 --> 00:11:21,712
          spicy mayo, eel sauce,
     a little bit more sriracha.

320
00:11:21,714 --> 00:11:24,248
       And then, I finish it off
             with sesame seeds. 

321
00:11:24,250 --> 00:11:26,918
         So, that right there is
         the -- oops -- volcano.

322
00:11:26,920 --> 00:11:29,320
See, it just erupted.           

323
00:11:29,322 --> 00:11:31,456
    Interesting.                
 Do you jump on it?             

324
00:11:31,458 --> 00:11:32,923
             -Yeah.             
     -Hit it with an elbow.     

325
00:11:32,925 --> 00:11:35,060
             I mean, you've just
              got to go at it.  

326
00:11:35,062 --> 00:11:36,528
 I was able to build            
a bite there, folks.            

327
00:11:36,530 --> 00:11:39,530
       Right. So, you got, like,
     a little nacho right there.

328
00:11:39,532 --> 00:11:41,266
    I don't care                
what you do with it,            

329
00:11:41,268 --> 00:11:43,601
 when you serve tuna            
    that fresh --               

330
00:11:43,603 --> 00:11:45,670
I mean, that's legit.           
That's really legit.            

331
00:11:45,672 --> 00:11:48,873
I'm not a huge sauce guy, but I 
think this is a show-stopper.   

332
00:11:48,875 --> 00:11:50,742
I mean, people see this come    
out, they're going to go, "Wow."

333
00:11:50,744 --> 00:11:52,143
            It's like an awesome
                little salad.   

334
00:11:52,145 --> 00:11:54,879
         And it looks cool, too.

335
00:11:54,881 --> 00:11:57,615
      Can I go?                 
             Go for it, dude.   

336
00:11:57,617 --> 00:12:00,351
 All right. Walking in the door,
        I got a volcano.        

337
00:12:00,353 --> 00:12:03,220
      Jason's just sort of      
  pushed the creative envelope. 

338
00:12:03,222 --> 00:12:04,756
  WOMAN: Delicious.             

339
00:12:04,758 --> 00:12:07,024
And you can feel like you're    
eating something special.       

340
00:12:07,026 --> 00:12:09,427
             When I started off,
   it was like a seafood market,

341
00:12:09,429 --> 00:12:10,962
             so I got all these 
              different awesome 

342
00:12:10,964 --> 00:12:13,698
              connections with  
              crabs and shrimp. 

343
00:12:13,700 --> 00:12:16,901
             FIERI:             
  And he's calling on them all  
to build this seafood sculpture.

344
00:12:16,903 --> 00:12:18,503
      I have a totem pole.      

345
00:12:18,505 --> 00:12:21,706
      All of my New Orleans     
favorites wrapped into one dish.

346
00:12:21,708 --> 00:12:24,041
    It's fresh seafood layer    
     upon layer upon layer.     

347
00:12:24,043 --> 00:12:28,379
 It looks like a totem pole with
  a crab in the middle of there.

348
00:12:28,381 --> 00:12:30,447
You have got a big imagination, 
     my friend.                 

349
00:12:30,449 --> 00:12:33,651
All right. I'm going to show you
 how to make the crab stuffing. 

350
00:12:33,653 --> 00:12:34,853
       Hit it.                  

351
00:12:34,855 --> 00:12:37,455
         Butter, celery,        
    garlic, onions, peppers,    

352
00:12:37,457 --> 00:12:39,991
         lump crab meat         
 fresh out of Lake Ponchartrain,

353
00:12:39,993 --> 00:12:41,325
         the claw meat.         

354
00:12:41,327 --> 00:12:44,729
And this is the stuffing that   
goes inside of the totem pole?  

355
00:12:44,731 --> 00:12:45,796
             -Right.            
            -Next in?           

356
00:12:45,798 --> 00:12:46,731
                I love dust.    

357
00:12:46,733 --> 00:12:48,399
       Crawfish boil, crab boil.

358
00:12:48,401 --> 00:12:50,668
        The blackening seasoning
           that we made earlier.

359
00:12:50,670 --> 00:12:52,470
               Gumbo fillet --  
             a little sassafras.

360
00:12:52,472 --> 00:12:53,871
      Grab them                 
  sassafras leaves.             

361
00:12:53,873 --> 00:12:55,005
    Little bit of               
   the love dust.               

362
00:12:55,007 --> 00:12:56,808
     You name these things?     
          -Absolutely.          

363
00:12:56,810 --> 00:12:59,543
           Blackening seasoning,
             water, lemon juice,

364
00:12:59,545 --> 00:13:01,545
       bread crumbs, and then --
    boom, there's your stuffing.

365
00:13:01,547 --> 00:13:03,080
 Boom, there it is.             

366
00:13:03,082 --> 00:13:04,749
         Now, we're going to get
           some soft-shell crabs

367
00:13:04,751 --> 00:13:06,083
                  ready for     
               the totem pole.  

368
00:13:06,085 --> 00:13:07,752
   And I'm a huge               
soft-shell crab fan.            

369
00:13:07,754 --> 00:13:09,087
When you get a chance           
  to come down here             

370
00:13:09,089 --> 00:13:12,156
and try true soft-shell crab    
done the right way --           

371
00:13:12,158 --> 00:13:13,891
    game changer.               
   Tons of flavor.              

372
00:13:13,893 --> 00:13:15,827
             Then, it goes into 
               the buttermilk.  

373
00:13:15,829 --> 00:13:17,561
                  And then,     
             into our fish fry. 

374
00:13:17,563 --> 00:13:18,963
                  And then,     
                into the oil.   

375
00:13:18,965 --> 00:13:20,565
            Eggplant.           
           -Beautiful.          

376
00:13:20,567 --> 00:13:22,033
     Let me see                 
   the totem pole.              

377
00:13:22,035 --> 00:13:23,968
       Here's that crab stuffing
             that we just made. 

378
00:13:23,970 --> 00:13:26,104
             Put a piece of this
        fried eggplant on there.

379
00:13:26,106 --> 00:13:27,505
             More crab stuffing.

380
00:13:27,507 --> 00:13:29,440
        -And this is hot?       
          -Absolutely.          

381
00:13:29,442 --> 00:13:31,242
          Got some more of that.

382
00:13:31,244 --> 00:13:33,645
            And then, here comes
           your soft-shell crab.

383
00:13:33,647 --> 00:13:36,381
             More crab stuffing,
               more eggplant.   

384
00:13:36,383 --> 00:13:37,815
          This is a cream sauce,

385
00:13:37,817 --> 00:13:42,387
  And then, hold it all together
         with this shrimp kebab.

386
00:13:42,389 --> 00:13:43,855
             More sauce on that.

387
00:13:43,857 --> 00:13:45,323
              And then, we need 
           some Parmesan cheese.

388
00:13:45,325 --> 00:13:48,059
        -Of course we do.       
 -Put a little greens on there. 

389
00:13:48,061 --> 00:13:49,660
You have issues.                
               Yeah.            

390
00:13:49,662 --> 00:13:51,061
     Good ones,                 
     but issues.                

391
00:13:51,063 --> 00:13:53,798
                     ♪♪         

392
00:13:53,800 --> 00:13:56,200
The batter on that crab --      
       money.                   

393
00:13:56,202 --> 00:13:57,401
                 Thank you.     

394
00:13:57,403 --> 00:13:59,537
I did not want to like          
 the crab stuffing,             

395
00:13:59,539 --> 00:14:00,804
  'cause I've never             
    heard of it.                

396
00:14:00,806 --> 00:14:02,206
And to me, it was just          
     a crab cake                

397
00:14:02,208 --> 00:14:04,475
that didn't get the love        
texture on the outside.         

398
00:14:04,477 --> 00:14:05,944
But this, right here,           
   works perfect.               

399
00:14:05,946 --> 00:14:07,879
You get this smooth,            
   creamy texture               

400
00:14:07,881 --> 00:14:10,014
   with the crunch              
 of the eggplant --             

401
00:14:10,016 --> 00:14:11,749
  and a good piece              
   of eggplant --               

402
00:14:11,751 --> 00:14:15,219
and then, you get the gravy.    
Then, you get that money bite.  

403
00:14:15,221 --> 00:14:17,354
That's like a roadside          
in Flavortown right there.      

404
00:14:17,356 --> 00:14:19,624
That's getting it done.         

405
00:14:19,626 --> 00:14:21,292
         The totem pole         
         is my favorite.        

406
00:14:21,294 --> 00:14:25,029
  I love the soft-shelled crab. 
      I love the eggplant.      

407
00:14:25,031 --> 00:14:27,965
 When I first really started to 
learn about Cajun creole cooking

408
00:14:27,967 --> 00:14:29,099
        was from this guy       
           right here.          

409
00:14:29,101 --> 00:14:30,501
    Kim Gardner, let me hear    
         what you think.        

410
00:14:30,503 --> 00:14:31,969
          -That's good.         
         -There you go.         

411
00:14:31,971 --> 00:14:33,304
       Kim says it's good,      
         I'll come here.        

412
00:14:33,306 --> 00:14:35,306
    I mean, this is a little    
      funky seafood shack.      

413
00:14:35,308 --> 00:14:36,708
      Will you expect this      
    kind of food out of them?   

414
00:14:36,710 --> 00:14:38,443
   GARDENER: When you look at   
     this place, you don't.     

415
00:14:38,445 --> 00:14:40,111
        But I would drive       
            for this.           

416
00:14:40,113 --> 00:14:41,779
         I got a hamper,        
           table nine!          

417
00:14:41,781 --> 00:14:43,380
     It's our very favorite     
           restaurant.          

418
00:14:43,382 --> 00:14:46,050
 Just heavenly goodness all the 
 way through every time I come. 

419
00:14:46,052 --> 00:14:48,720
             FIERI:             
 The way you treat food, and the
 imagination you have as a chef,

420
00:14:48,722 --> 00:14:50,722
      and the appreciation      
  you have for fresh seafood -- 

421
00:14:50,724 --> 00:14:52,523
you're doing a great job, man.  
                Appreciate it.  

422
00:14:52,525 --> 00:14:54,993
     Excellent.                 

423
00:14:54,995 --> 00:14:56,995
           Coming up,           
   another New Orleans gem...   

424
00:14:56,997 --> 00:14:58,196
  This is on point.             

425
00:14:58,198 --> 00:14:59,998
        ...getting saucy        
      with their oysters...     

426
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:01,866
       We're breaking boundaries
             here on "Triple D."

427
00:15:01,868 --> 00:15:04,601
     ...and going unexpected    
    with a familiar favorite.   

428
00:15:04,603 --> 00:15:06,804
If tater salad wasn't good      
 enough, we're gonna            
   fry it for you.              

429
00:15:10,377 --> 00:15:13,243
                     ♪♪         

430
00:15:13,245 --> 00:15:15,713
     So, for our final stop     
     on this special edition    

431
00:15:15,715 --> 00:15:17,448
          of "Triple D"         
         in New Orleans,        

432
00:15:17,450 --> 00:15:19,517
     we're here to check out    
       a joint on Tulane.       

433
00:15:19,519 --> 00:15:21,251
         It started off         
           as a prank,          

434
00:15:21,253 --> 00:15:23,655
      and turned out to be      
         the real deal.         

435
00:15:23,657 --> 00:15:25,723
      Husband and wife team     
       making traditional       

436
00:15:25,725 --> 00:15:29,127
 New Orleans specialties in not 
   such a traditional manner.   

437
00:15:29,129 --> 00:15:32,263
             This is            
       Avery's on Tulane.       

438
00:15:32,265 --> 00:15:33,798
               Buffalo shrimp   
                  po' boy.      

439
00:15:33,800 --> 00:15:35,599
    Whenever I have people in   
        from out of town,       

440
00:15:35,601 --> 00:15:37,001
    I always take them here,    

441
00:15:37,003 --> 00:15:38,736
      'cause it's the best      
      New Orleans cuisine.      

442
00:15:38,738 --> 00:15:40,872
         Stuffed artichoke balls
            with crawfish sauce.

443
00:15:40,874 --> 00:15:43,674
      I came here one time,     
  and I was completely hooked.  

444
00:15:43,676 --> 00:15:45,610
     FIERI: But at one point    
        for Justin Pitard       

445
00:15:45,612 --> 00:15:47,078
     and his wife, Christy,     

446
00:15:47,080 --> 00:15:50,881
    the very idea of opening    
this joint was, well, laughable.

447
00:15:50,883 --> 00:15:52,216
        Now, how did you        
